reviewText:
Pros:
- Throwing stars;
- The world is huge, with more diversity than Skyrim's barren landscape;
- Large amount of magic effects. A user created spell can have eight effects;
- More weapon types than you can swing with;
- A Mudcrab merchant, a plant named Charles, dead explorer named Peek-At-Choo and a statue that gives you a golden sword;
- Did I mention throwing stars?;
- One exploit allows for an unlimited summoning of monsters.
- Hours of content rewards exploration with great items. Does Skyrim have that? (Look up the Ring of Pop Je);
- Exploits allow for OPness beyond Chuck Norris.

Cons-
- Graphics are dated, 2002 is soooo last decade;
- A bit buggy, save often;
- Staffs are a weapon type better left on the ground;
- Exploits sing their siren song for you to use them;
- Skyrim has more mods. Damn you MLP fans.

If you're not satisified with summoning an army of ogres and making Shrek jokes get your money back.

I have played morrowind since I was 11, not long after it was out. I'm now 22 (almost 23) and I still love playing this game.

if you want to use the free add-ons (available on the offical TES site) Remeber to extract into the STEAM file of morrowind. C:\...\Steam\steamapps\common\Morrowind\Data Files (yours might be different at the start, hence the ...")

This game has a similar learning curve to EVE online (aka more of a learning cliff)

